42. Adulescens quidam. In Apollodorus this young man, according to Donatus, was no other than the barber himself, who had just rega turned from cutting off the young woman’s hair, which was one of the usual ceremonies of mourning among the Greeks. This circumstance Terence has judiciously altered, that he might not shock the Roman spectatore with manners so very foreign to their own. —45. Hic vicinia. Comp. Andr. i. 1. 43. -- 47. Ea sita erat, διο. “ The corpse was laid out opposite the weeping virgin.’' The poet, says Donatus, has managed this part of the narration with so much address, that we are not so much affected at the death of the mother, as at the distress of the beautiful virgin3 especially as we find in the catastrophe, that the death of this woman gives the poet abetter opportunity of establish- ing the general happiness. — 48.
